    {
      "_type": "text",
      "contents": "\n\n(** ** Lagrange's theorem *)\n\n(** Lagrange's Theorem - Given a finite group [G] and a finite subgroup [H] of [G], the order of [H] divides the order of [G].\n\nNote that constructively, a subgroup of a finite group cannot be shown to be finite without excluded middle. We therefore have to assume it is. This in turn implies that the subgroup is decidable. *)\n"
    },
    {
      "_type": "sentence",
      "contents": "Definition divides_fcard_subgroup {U : Univalence}\n  (G : Group) (H : Subgroup G) {fin_G : Finite G} {fin_H : Finite H}\n  : (fcard H | fcard G).",
      "messages": [],
      "goals": [
        {
          "_type": "goal",
          "name": null,
          "conclusion": "(fcard H | fcard G)",
          "hypotheses": [
            {
              "_type": "hypothesis",
              "names": [
                "U"
              ],
              "body": null,
              "type": "Univalence"
            },
            {
              "_type": "hypothesis",
              "names": [
                "G"
              ],
              "body": null,
              "type": "Group"
            },
            {
              "_type": "hypothesis",
              "names": [
                "H"
              ],
              "body": null,
              "type": "Subgroup G"
            },
            {
              "_type": "hypothesis",
              "names": [
                "fin_G"
              ],
              "body": null,
              "type": "Finite G"
            },
            {
              "_type": "hypothesis",
              "names": [
                "fin_H"
              ],
              "body": null,
              "type": "Finite H"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "_type": "text",
      "contents": "\n"
    },
